# Google Loses Antitrust Case On Search Tool

Judge Rules Company Is Illegal Monopoly

# SENDING MIXED SIGNALS

BY DAVID MCCARE

WASHINGTON — Google acted illegally to maintain a monopoly in search search, a federal judge ruled on Monday, a landmark decision that strikes at the center of tech giants at the heart of a new antitrust battle that may reshape the way the internet is run.

Judge Amit P. Mehta Jr., District Court for the District of Columbia said on a 27-page ruling that Google had abused a monopoly over the internet business. The Justice Department and states had sued Google, accusing it of illegally cementing its dominance in part, by paying other companies to keep their search results off of Google’s search engine and to pay for advertising on Google’s search queries on their smartphones and web browsers.

“After having carefully considered and weighed the various testimony and evidence, the court is unable to determine whether Google is a monopoly, and it has not acted on its nomination to its deputy,” Judge Mehta said in his ruling.

The court said Google’s decision was “not a clear and binding precedent” in the matter, but the court “is not convinced that the evidence presented by the government is sufficient to establish that Google has a monopoly over the internet.”

The ruling is the latest in a series of legal actions that have been brought against Google, including a class action lawsuit against Google, which was built on its search engine and has been accused of falsely associating with a search engine that has been used to manipulate Google’s search results.

“This is the most important moment in the history of the internet,” the judge said. “It is a day of clarity and a day of justice. It is a day of hope and a day of hope for the internet.”

The case is being heard in front of a jury of six judges, and the jury will decide whether Google has a monopoly over the internet.
